# Option A — Atlas connection string (paste from Atlas → Connect → Drivers)
# Use either mongodb+srv://… or the "standard" mongodb://host1:27017,host2:27017,… URI (often fixes TLS issues).
# Replace USER/PASSWORD; URL-encode the password if it contains @ : / ? # [ ] etc.
# Add retryWrites + write concern if missing: …&retryWrites=true&w=majority
MONGODB_URI=

# Option B — standard connection without pasting a full URI (avoids mongodb+srv DNS; good for Netlify TLS issues)
# Copy seed hostnames + replica set name from Atlas → Connect → Drivers → "standard connection string".
# MONGODB_USER=
# MONGODB_PASSWORD=
# MONGODB_SEED_HOSTS=shard-00-00.xxx.mongodb.net:27017,shard-00-01.xxx.mongodb.net:27017,shard-00-02.xxx.mongodb.net:27017
# MONGODB_REPLICA_SET=atlas-xxxx-shard-0
# MONGODB_AUTH_SOURCE=admin

# Option C — SRV only if B is not used (often flaky TLS from serverless)
# MONGODB_USER=
# MONGODB_PASSWORD=
# MONGODB_HOST=cluster0.xxxxx.mongodb.net

# Optional database name (default: mongodb_dx_copilot)
MONGODB_DB_NAME=

# TLS to Atlas (OpenSSL "tlsv1 alert internal error"): app prefers IPv4 DNS order + IPv4 sockets.
# MONGODB_DNS_FAMILY=auto — use Node defaults (e.g. local Mongo on IPv6-only localhost).
# MONGODB_DNS_ORDER=verbatim — skip dns.setDefaultResultOrder("ipv4first").
# MONGODB_TLS_MIN_VERSION=default — skip forcing TLS 1.2 minimum (rare).
# MONGODB_TLS_INSECURE_DIAGNOSTIC=1 — only for debugging: relax TLS cert checks (do not use in production).
# If TLS still fails, use Option B (seeds) or paste Atlas "standard" mongodb://… URI into MONGODB_URI (not mongodb+srv).
# The app marks `mongodb` as a server external in next.config.mjs so the driver is not webpack-bundled (avoids broken TLS in serverless).
